         <abstract>
            <p>The numerical solution of exterior problems is typically accomplished by introducing an artificial, far field boundary and solving the equations on a truncated domain. For hyperbolic systems, boundary conditions at this boundary are often derived by imposing a principle of no reflection. However, waves with spherical symmetry in gas dynamics satisfy equations where incoming and outgoing Riemann variables are coupled. This suggests that `natural' reflections may be important. We propose a reflecting boundary condition based on an asymptotic solution of the far field equations. We obtain nonlinear energy estimates for the truncated problem and present numerical experiments to validate our theory.</p>
          </abstract>
